Introduction
Behavioural problems are observed frequently in psychiatric disorders. They take numerous forms, including withdrawal, avoidance, compulsions and various types of safety seeking behaviours. As such, it is important that the therapist elicits the roles these behavioural features play in the maintenance of the patient’s problems.

Key features: To help the patient gain insight into the effect of his/her behaviours with respect to the problems. This can be done through the use of questioning, diaries and monitoring procedures.. Two features need to be considered: 
